Wyoming Game and Fish reports new cases of chronic wasting disease

The Wyoming Game and Fish Department is reporting new discoveries of chronic wasting disease in 2 hunt areas.

Chronic wasting disease is a fatal neurological disease that can hit deer, elk and moose.

The department said its surveillance program found the disease in a doe mule deer from deer hunt area 123, northeast of Lovell. It also found it in a cow elk from elk hunt area 108, southwest of Rawlins.

Both of the new hunt areas are bordered by or overlap hunt areas where the disease was found previously.

Scott Edberg, deputy chief of the game department's wildlife division, said the department takes the disease seriously and continues to research vaccines and evaluate options to try to prevent its spread.
